Why is unresolved tension an invitation?

I don’t think unresolved tension is always an invitation.

It’s an invitation if the system has both:

1. a way to reduce the tension, and
2. enough expected value in trying.

A cliffhanger in a novel works because your brain has learned that stories usually resolve. A hanging chord works because your auditory system has internalized the statistical structure of music. A puzzle works because it looks solvable.

If there is no apparent path to resolution, tension stops being playful and becomes frustration.

So “invitation” isn’t an intrinsic property of the tension. It’s a property of the interaction between the tension and the learner.

