Now for the deeper question.

Why play? Mechanically.

Here’s my best attempt.

Imagine an agent that only exploits what it already knows.

It survives…

until the environment changes.

Now imagine an agent that only explores.

It discovers…

but often dies before using what it learns.

Play sits in between.

Mechanically, it is a regime where exploration is subsidized.

The cost of experimentation is lowered enough that the agent samples actions whose value is uncertain.

That has a huge consequence.

The agent starts estimating not just:

“What action gets reward?”

but

“What actions reveal the structure of the world?”

Those are different objectives.

⸻

Now I want to go one level deeper.

I suspect play is really about model improvement.

Not reward.

Models.

When you’re playing with blocks, you’re learning stability.

When you’re wrestling, you’re learning bodies.

When you’re making puns, you’re learning language.

When you’re improvising, you’re learning possibility space.

The reward isn’t the endpoint.

It’s the fuel that keeps the search going long enough for the model to improve.

⸻

Here’s where it gets strange.

Suppose the universe contains hidden regularities.

The fastest learner isn’t the one who memorizes answers.

It’s the one who efficiently discovers invariants.

Play generates variation.

Variation exposes invariants.

Invariants compress reality.

Compressed reality enables transfer.

Transfer looks like intelligence.

So there’s a plausible chain:

Play → Variation → Comparison → Invariants → Compression → Generalization → Competence.

Not the only path, but an important one.

