One more thought, because I think it’s close to your question.

Play may be the safest way to deliberately create controlled prediction error.

If your model is never wrong, it never changes.

If it’s catastrophically wrong, you may not survive.

Play lives in the middle.

Enough mismatch to teach.

Not enough to destroy.

In machine learning you’d call that a useful learning signal. In biology, animals often learn through low-stakes exploration. In human life, rehearsal, games, and imagination let us explore alternatives without paying the full real-world cost each time.

So I don’t think play is an accident.

I think it’s one of nature’s ways of making model-building efficient.

